value.value: Any nerve (FBbt:00005105) that is part of some prothoracic segment (FBbt:00000017).

Larval intersegmental nerve of the prothoracic segment. Similar to the A1-A7 nerves, it has two roots; an anterior root that is formed by neurons of the anteriorly adjacent neuromere, and a posterior root, that is formed by neurons of the same neuromere as the nerve (Campos-Ortega and Hartenstein, 1997). Proximally it shares a glial sheath with the segmental nerve before branching from it at the border between the prothorax and mesothorax (Campos-Ortega and Hartenstein, 1997). It then bends anterolaterally and, upon leaving the surface of the ventral longitudinal muscle, receives a branch from the prothoracic lateral sensory cluster (Campos-Ortega and Hartenstein, 1997). Its main trunk continues dorsally and innervates the dorsal sensory cluster and dorsal musculature (Campos-Ortega and Hartenstein, 1997).

Larval segmental nerve of the prothoracic segment. Similar to the A1-A7 nerves, it has two roots, anterior and posterior, both formed from neurons of the same segment as the nerve (Campos-Ortega and Hartenstein, 1997). Proximally it shares a glial sheath with the intersegmental nerve before branching from it at the border between the prothorax and mesothorax (Campos-Ortega and Hartenstein, 1997). It receives sensory fibers from the ventral monoscolopidial chordotonal organ, Keilin organ and vc1 sensillum (Campos-Ortega and Hartenstein, 1997). It gives off a thick branch to the ventral intersegmental muscle, while its main branch continues to the ventral transverse musculature, the ventral Kolbchen and the vc2 sensillum (Campos-Ortega and Hartenstein, 1997).

Larval multidendritic neuron of the ventral' sensory cluster of the prothoracic segment (Campos-Ortega and Hartenstein, 1997). There are four of these on each side, all of which have axons that fasciculate with the prothoracic segmental nerve (Campos-Ortega and Hartenstein, 1997).

definition.value: There are no multidendritic neurons in the ventral cluster in thoracic segments.

Larval intersegmental nerve of the mesothoracic segment. Similar to the A1-A7 nerves, it has two roots; an anterior root that is formed by neurons of the anteriorly adjacent neuromere, and a posterior root, that is formed by neurons of the same neuromere as the nerve (Campos-Ortega and Hartenstein, 1997). Proximally it shares a glial sheath with the segmental nerve (Campos-Ortega and Hartenstein, 1997). It receives a branch from the mesothoracic lateral sensory cluster (Campos-Ortega and Hartenstein, 1997). Its main trunk continues dorsally and innervates the dorsal sensory cluster and dorsal musculature (Campos-Ortega and Hartenstein, 1997).
